data.content:
This code **does not use `Thread.Abort`** — there's nothing to migrate on that front. It uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep`, all of which remain supported in .NET 8.

That said, for a .NET 8 migration, the idiomatic modernization would be to replace manual `Thread` management with `Task`-based parallelism:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Delay(100, ct);
            item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
        });
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` guidance** (for when you do encounter it elsewhere):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` + cooperative cancellation |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks | `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Remove entirely — not needed |

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8. The fix is always cooperative cancellation via `CancellationTokenSource`.
